{{About|the ethical obligation of U.S. [[mental health professionals]]|the [[international relations]] concept|Responsibility to protect}}
{{multiple issues|
{{Globalize/US|article|date=December 2010}}
{{Page numbers needed|date=May 2017}}
}}

The '''duty to protect''' is the responsibility of a [[mental health professional]] to protect patients and others from foreseeable harm.  If a client makes statements that suggest suicidal or homicidal ideation, the clinician has the responsibility to take steps to warn intended victims, and if necessary, initiate [[involuntary commitment]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Corey|first1=Gerald Corey |last2=Corey|first2=Marianne Schneider |last3=Callahan|first3=Patrick |date=2007 |title=Issues and Ethics in the Helping Professions |edition=7th |publisher=Brooks/Cole/Thomson Learning |location=Belmont, CA |isbn=978-0-534-61443-0 |oclc=65465556 }}</ref>{{Page needed|date=April 2015}}

==History==
The duty to protect was established by ''[[Tarasoff v. Regents of the University of California]]'',<ref>{{cite book |last=Simon|first=Robert I. |title=Concise Guide to Psychiatry and the Law for Clinicians |edition=3rd |series=Concise guides |publisher=[[American Psychiatric Publishing]] |location=Washington, DC |date=2001 |isbn=978-1-58562-024-1 |oclc=45202323 }}</ref>{{Page needed|date=April 2015}} which has been widely adopted by other states.<ref name="jaapl">
{{cite journal |last1=Weinstock|first1=Robert |last2=Vari|first2=Gabor |last3=Leong|first3=Gregory B. |last4=Silva|first4=J. Arturo |date=December 2006 |title=Back to the Past in California: A Temporary Retreat to a ''Tarasoff'' Duty to Warn |volume=34 |issue=4 |pages=523–528 |journal=Journal of the American Academy for Psychiatry and the Law |pmid=17185483 |accessdate=2008-01-08 |url=http://www.jaapl.org/content/34/4/523.full }}</ref>  This case determined that the clinician has the [[duty to warn]] an identifiable victim. {{citation needed span |text=''[[Jablonski by Pahls v. United States]]'' extended this responsibility to include the involuntary commitment of a dangerous individual. |date=April 2015}} ''[[Ewing v. Goldstein]]'' extended the duty to protect to include acting upon the statements of third parties that indicate possible threat, and determined that it was not sufficiently discharged by initiating involuntary commitment; warning identifiable victims is also necessary.<ref name="jaapl" />

The 42 C.F.R. $2.20 and <u>Hasenei v U.S.,</u> 541F. Supp. 999 (D.Md 1982). The federal law prohibits disclosure unless you obtain a court order or you can make the report without identifying the individual who threatens to commit the crime as a patient.

